Build Phases

### Phase 0 вҖ” Verify all three MCPs individually
Get Blender MCP, UE5 MCP, and Premiere MCP each running in Claude Desktop and confirm basic tool calls work before writing any orchestrator code.

Deliverable: single `claude_desktop_config.json` with all three servers registered and tested.

### Phase 1 вҖ” FORGE skeleton
Create the repo structure, `forge.yaml` config schema, FastMCP server entrypoint, and state store. No app logic yet вҖ” just the server boots and Claude can call `get_pipeline_status`.

Deliverable: `forge_server.py` boots, registers with Claude Desktop, returns status.

### Phase 2 вҖ” Render watcher
Implement the `watchdog` file system monitor on the pipeline folder. When a new file lands in `blender/` or `ue5/`, the state store updates and the orchestrator knows the render is complete.

Deliverable: `render_watcher.py` detects new EXR/PNG/MP4 files and logs them to state.

### Phase 3 вҖ” High-level tool surface
Wire `render_scene`, `get_render_status`, `import_render`, and `run_pipeline` to the underlying app adapters. This is where the cross-app magic works for the first time.

Deliverable: single prompt triggers Blender render, watcher detects output, Premiere imports it.

### Phase 4 вҖ” End-to-end test
Full pipeline test: one Claude prompt вҶ’ Blender render вҶ’ auto-detected by watcher вҶ’ imported into Premiere timeline вҶ’ basic cut applied вҶ’ export.

Deliverable: recorded demo, test log.

### Phase 5 вҖ” Documentation and release
Write README, CLAUDE.md spec, and `forge.yaml` reference. Tag v0.1.0.

Deliverable: public GitHub repo ready for contributors.

